Normally I would recommend using [ExecutorService.invokeAll](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/17/docs/api/java.base/java/util/concurrent/ExecutorService.html#invokeAll(java.util.Collection,long,java.util.concurrent.TimeUnit)), which allows the submission of any number of tasks with a timeout and which will cancel any tasks which haven’t completed when that timeout expires.

But you have stated in a comment that you want to be able to submit tasks in smaller parallelized groups, for example having no more than three running concurrently at a time.

You can create a thread pool with a limited amount of parallelism:

    ExecutorService executor = Executors.newFixedThreadPool(3);

The challenge here is that you want the timeout to start when the task starts, not when the task is submitted.  Since a submitted task has no way to access its own Future, I would use a [SynchronousQueue](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/17/docs/api/java.base/java/util/concurrent/SynchronousQueue.html) to wait for that Future to be passsed from the submitting thread:

    ScheduledExecutorService cancelScheduler =
        Executors.newSingleThreadScheduledExecutor();

    for (int i : array) {
        SynchronousQueue&lt;Runnable&gt; cancelQueue = new SynchronousQueue&lt;&gt;();

        Future&lt;?&gt; task = executor.submit(() -&gt; {
            Runnable canceler = cancelQueue.take();
            cancelScheduler.schedule(canceler, 5, TimeUnit.SECONDS);

            Goring goring = new Goring();
            goring.goring(i);

            return null;
        });

        cancelQueue.put(() -&gt; task.cancel(true));
    }

    executor.shutdown();
    cancelScheduler.shutdown();

As the name implies, [Executors.newSingleThreadScheduledExecutor()](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/17/docs/api/java.base/java/util/concurrent/Executors.html#newSingleThreadScheduledExecutor()) uses just one thread for all scheduling, which is perfectly suitable for your purposes, since the scheduled tasks only call Future.cancel, which takes a negligible amount of time.

The reason for having `return null;` in the task is that returning a value from the lambda makes it a Callable rather than a Runnable. (Runnable&#39;s `run` method has a return type of `void`, so the presence of a returned value tells the compiler this lambda cannot possibly represent a Runnable.)  This means its signature implicitly has `throws Exception` in it, so there is no need to catch the InterruptedException that might be thrown by `cancelQueue.take()`.

