The shortcut is to convert each `char` array to a `String` since `String` has a `contains` method that gives us the answer that we want. `contains()` accepts any `CharSequence` as argument, so a `String` works, and a possibly slightly cheaper variant is to wrap `sublist` and `sublist2` in `CharBuffer`s rather than converting them too to `String`.

    char[] list = { &#39;A&#39;, &#39;B&#39;, &#39;B&#39;, &#39;C&#39;, &#39;B&#39;, &#39;D&#39; };
    char[] sublist = { &#39;B&#39;, &#39;C&#39;, &#39;B&#39; };
    char[] sublist2 = { &#39;A&#39;, &#39;B&#39;, &#39;D&#39; };

    String listString = new String(list);
    System.out.println(&quot;Contains sublist? &quot; + listString.contains(CharBuffer.wrap(sublist)));
    System.out.println(&quot;Contains sublist2? &quot; + listString.contains(CharBuffer.wrap(sublist2)));

Output:

&gt;     Contains sublist? true
&gt;     Contains sublist2? false

## What went wrong in your code?

What happens in your inner `for` loop doesn’t matter since after the loop finishes you unconditionally return `true`. So if `sublist` has length at least 1 (is not empty), you will reach that `return statement` and return `true`. If `sublist` is empty, the outer `for` loop is skipped, so you get down to the bottom of the method and return `false` (in spite of the empty list conventionally being regarded as contained in any list).

Instead from each position in `list` (not `sublist`) you need to search for a position where the chars from the two lists are *different*. If you find such a difference, the sublist is not contained at the current position in `list`, and you should try the next position.

